<br>
If this story does indeed to turn out to be true you have my deepest sympathies.  However,  I found it hard to fathom that a woman with a husband and 3 children would leave those she loves in complete darkness with little time to make preparations and hide from them the seriousness of such an illness.  There are cancers that can show minimal outside effects (with treatments) however if her cancer was that progressed, that widely dispersed and to such a degree it was untreatable or unoperable ... I again find difficulty in seeing her symptoms would not have been noticable by those she was with.  Cancer ravishes the body and causes great pain.  At her stage her illness should have been very apparent, even if not cureable .. they would undoubtly given her multiple medications to subside any pain or minimize her symptoms as best possible.  She would have had a huge extent of doctor visitations upon the discovery of her cancer and most likely hospitalization. <br>
<br>
As upsetting as someone questioning this might be (if indeed truthful), I found nothing demeaning or harmful in what Vehnn posted.  He simply asked for verification.  <br>
<br>
If this is untruthful I find it to be truly sick.  Cancer is nothing to be taken lightly.  To use such a thing for whatever reason and to upset many people on a lie is &lt;place various derogatory words here&gt;.<br>
<br>
Im sure I'll get flamed for this by some but the truth is a great deal of that story leaves itself open to question.  I am simply stating some of the things that I could see that would lead to such questions.  Maybe a great deal was left out of the post...or mistated.  Again if this is true, you and your family are in my prayers and I am sorry for your lose.  My father heads cancer research and surgical pathogy at Johns Hopkins, I see and hear the tragedy of cancer often and can only imagine what those close to a cancer patient have to endure.  I would wish it on no one.<br>
